
This document explains the way banishment works in the psionicist
guild.  It's based on a number of posts to the hipsi board in
November 1996.  This is subject to change according to the general
consensus of the high psionicists.

Banishment is the ultimate penalty that can be imposed upon a member
of the guild.  A banished player is cast out of the guild, and is
prevented from joining any other guilds.  As such, this isn't a
step to be taken lightly.  What's grounds for banishment in the
psi guild?  That's largely up to the high psionicists - they are
free to set guild policies, so long as those policies do not
contradict MUD rules.  One thing that's sure to bring you up for
banishment is knowingly abusing bugs, -especially- guild-related
ones.

The banishment process is as follows:  First, a complaint is posted
on the high psionicist board, by either the wizard guildmaster (in
the case of bug abuse) or by a player hipsi (in the case of anything
else).  This complaint should give the players' name and the reason why
banishment should be considered.

Next, -before- any other posts on the matter, the player accused will
have the chance to offer a defense.  If he chooses not to, the wizard
guildmaster will post to say so.

After the defense or notice is posted, other hipsis will post a yes
or no vote to the hipsi board.  Banishment will occur if a) at least
1/4 of the active hipsis, with a minimum of 5 (or all, if there are
fewer than 5 active hipsis) vote, and b) at least 2/3 of those votes
are 'yes'.

In the event of a banishment vote, the player in question will be
offered the chance to leave the guild of their own accord through
Grimtila first; otherwise, they will be banished.

One last word:  Do -not- attempt to buy votes.  It is illegal, and
it is the only way in which you can (and will) be banished without
a vote.
